.pl 62
                            Chapter 5


                 DSI-32 ASSEMBLER PSEUDO OPCODES


5.1  INTRODUCTION

The  DSI-32  Assembler has a variety of pseudo opcodes to  enable 
the programmer to control aspects of data and code storage.

  Pseudo-op			Description		 Section
  ---------			-----------		 -------
Symbol Creation      create a symbol, and specifies its	    5.2
		     type and value
Data generation	     controls the output of code and data   5.3
		     constants
Storage Allocation   allocates storage for run-time data    5.4
Listing Control	     controls the format of list-file	    5.5
Linkage Control	     manages the external addressing modes  5.6
Segment Control	     defines the different module segments  5.7
Module Control	     defines the module name and execution  5.8
		     address
Procedure Management defines the procedure structure       Ch. 6

pseudo-ops  are Assembler commands which may be embedded into the 
source statements of a program. There are several types of DSI-32 
assembler  pseudo-ops as can be seen from  above.  Some  generate 
data,  some  generate  code  while others  only  control  listing 
formats  or  how code or data is to be generated.  The  following 
sections detail how the various pseudo-ops perform their tasks.
DSI-32  Assembler pseudo-ops may optionally be preceded by a  dot 
(e.g. .BYTE) to conform with other 32000 assemblers.
.pa
5.2  SYMBOL CREATION PSEUDO-OP (EQU)

Format:   <symbol>:[: | -]  EQU  <expression>

description:
          <symbol>       is  a symbol name.  The symbol name must 
                         be followed by one colon (:), two colons 
                         (::), or colon minus (:-).

          EQU            is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   is a constant or an expression.   It may 
                         evaluate to any type and value.  Forward 
                         references to symbols are not permitted.

The  EQU  pseudo-op creates a symbol.  The pseudo-op  causes  the 
Assembler to evaluate the expression and assign the value to  the 
symbol.  The  expression  must  evaluate  to  one  of  the  types 
described  in Section 2.5.   The symbol's scope may be local (:), 
exported (::) or imported/exported (:-).

Once  a  symbol  has been defined,  subsequent  portions  of  the 
program  may  reference that symbol directly or as a term  in  an 
expression.  The  type  of the symbol restricts  the  permissible 
places where it may referenced.  The first eight characters of  a 
symbol's  name must be unique.  Note that in the extended version 
of  the DSI-32 the first 29 characters of a symbol name  must  be 
unique.  Note a  symbol's name is case dependent,  thus LABEL and 
Label are different symbols.

Examples:

  1  LABELA:  .EQU   12
  2  LABELB::  EQU   10(FP) + LABELA
  3  LABELC:  .EQU   'ABCD'

Example 1 defines the symbol LABELA. The pseudo-op assigns LABELA 
the value 0000000C and the Immediate type.

Example 2 defines the global symbol LABELB. The pseudo-op assigns 
LABELB the value of the expression  10(FP)+LABELA.  If LABELA has 
value IM  0000000C, LABELB is assigned the value FP 00000016.

Example 3 defines the symbol LABELC. The pseudo-op assigns LABELC 
the Immediate type with a value of 41424344
.pa
5.3  DATA GENERATION PSEUDO-OPS

The  data  generation pseudo-ops store data  in  the  instruction 
stream during assembly time.

   Pseudo-op     Description
   ---------     -----------
     BYTE	 store byte-long data
     SBYTE	 store signed byte-long data
     WORD	 store word-long data
     SWORD	 store signed word-long data
     DOUBLE	 store double word-long data
     SDOUBLE	 store signed double word-long data
     FLOAT	 store single-precision floating point number
     LONG	 store double-precision floating point number
     FIELD	 store bit field
     IF          conditional assembly of the following code
     ENDIF       terminate appropriate IF condition
.pa
5.3.1  BYTE pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>] BYTE [[<repetition-factor>]] {<expression> | 
                                                  <string> } ,,,

description:
          <label>        an optional label.

          BYTE           is the pseudo opcode.

          <repetition-factor>
                         (optional) specifies the number of times 
                         to  repeat the specified data byte.   It 
                         must be an expression which evaluates to 
                         a    non-negative    immediate     type. 
                         <repetition  factor> must be enclosed in 
                         square brackets "[]".

          <expression>   specifies the value of the data byte. It 
                         must evaluate to an immediate type  with 
                         a value in the range -128 to 255.

          <string>       specifies a string.  A string is entered 
                         in  memory left to right.  A string must 
                         fit on a single assembler line.

The  BYTE   pseudo-op generates  byte  constants.  The  Assembler 
stores  the  bytes  in  the object file at  the  current  address 
specified  by the Location Counter.   If  <repetition-factor>  is 
greater  than one,  or more than one  expression  is   specified, 
the  bytes are stored in consecutive ascending sequence  starting 
at the current address.

If <string> is specified,  the ASCII contents are stored left  to 
right with each character occupying one byte.

NOTE:     <expression>  may  have string constants as  terms.  In 
          this  case the assembler treats the ASCII value of  the 
          string  as a double-word integer.   The  expression  is 
          evaluated and the result is stored in a single byte.  A 
          string  used  in  a  term  may be  no  more  than  four 
          characters  in  length,  otherwise  an  error  will  be 
          reported.
.pa
Examples:

  1.  0000000  PC  0C		BYTE   12
  2.  0000001  PC  010101010101	BYTE   [6]  1
  3.  0000007  PC  434241414243	BYTE   'CBAABC'
  4.  000000D  PC  41420D	BYTE   'AB',H'0D
  5.  0000010  PC  20		BYTE   '@'/2

Example 1 places 0C in a byte at address 00000000 PC.

Example  2 places 1  (repeated 6 times) in six consecutive  bytes 
starting at 00000001 PC.

Example  3 places the ASCII values of 'CBAABC' in six consecutive 
bytes starting at 00000007 PC.

Example 4 places the ASCII values of 'AB' starting at 0000000D PC 
followed by a 0D byte.

Example  5 places the value of the expression '@'/2  at  location 
00000010 PC.
.pa
5.3.2  SBYTE pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>] SBYTE [[<repetition-factor>]] {<expression> |
                                                   <string> } ,,,

description:
          <label>        an optional label.

          SBYTE          is the pseudo opcode.

          <repetition-factor>
                         (optional) specifies the number of times 
                         to  repeat the specified data byte.   It 
                         must be an expression which evaluates to 
                         a    non-negative    immediate     type. 
                         <repetition-factor>  must be enclosed in 
                         square brackets "[]".

          <expression>   specifies the value of the data byte. It 
                         must  evaluate to an immediate type with 
                         a value in the range -128 to 127.

          <string>       specifies a string.  A string is entered 
                         in memory left to right.  A string  must 
                         fit on a single assembler line.

The   SBYTE  pseudo-op  generates  signed  byte  constants.   The 
Assembler  stores  the bytes in the object file  at  the  current 
address  specified  by the  Location  Counter.   If  <repetition-
factor>  is greater than one,  or more than one   expression   is  
specified, the bytes are stored in consecutive ascending sequence 
starting at the current address.

NOTE:     <expression>  may  have string constants as  terms.  In 
          this  case the assembler treats the ASCII value of  the 
          string  as  a double-word integer.   The expression  is 
          evaluated and the result is stored in a single byte.  A 
          string  used  in  a  term may  be  no  more  than  four 
          characters  in  length,  otherwise  an  error  will  be 
          reported.
.pa
Examples:

  1.  0000000  PC  FE		SBYTE   -2
  2.  0000001  PC  010101010101	SBYTE   [6]  1
  3.  0000007  PC  434241414243	SBYTE   'CBAABC'
  4.  000000D  PC  41420D	SBYTE   'AB',H'0D
  5.  0000010  PC  20		SBYTE   '@'/2

Example 1 places FE in a byte at address 00000000 PC.

Example  2 places 1  (repeated 6 times) in six consecutive  bytes 
starting at 00000001 PC.

Example 3 places the ASCII values of 'CBAABC' in six  consecutive 
bytes starting at 00000007 PC.

Example 4 places the ASCII values of 'AB' starting at 0000000D PC 
followed by a 0D byte.

Example  5  places the value of the expression '@'/2 at  location 
00000010 PC.
.pa
5.3.3  WORD pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>] WORD [[<repetition-factor]] {<expression> |
                                                 <string>},,,

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          WORD           is the pseudo-op name.

          <repetition-factor>
                         (optional) specifies the number of times 
                         to  repeat the specified data word.   It 
                         must be an expression which evaluates to 
                         a    non-negative    immediate     type. 
                         <repetition-factor>  must be enclosed in 
                         square brackets "[]".

          <expression>   specifies the value of the data word. It 
                         must evaluate to an immediate type  with 
                         a value in the range -128 to 65535

          <string>       specifies a string constant.  Unless the 
                         string is a term in an expression it may 
                         be no longer than two characters.

The WORD pseudo-op generates word length constants. The Assembler 
stores  the  words  in the object file  at  the  current  address 
specified  by  the Location Counter.   If <repetition-factor>  is 
greater  than one,  or more than one  expression  is   specified, 
the  words are stored in consecutive ascending sequence  starting 
at the current address.  The least significant byte of a word  is 
stored at first and the most significant next.
NOTE:  <expression>  may have string constants as terms.  In this 
     case the assembler treats the ASCII value of the string as a 
     double-word  integer.   The expression is evaluated and  the 
     result is stored in a single word.   A string used in a term 
     may be no more than four characters in length,  otherwise an 
     error will be reported.

Examples:

  1.  00000000  PC  0200		WORD  8/4
  2.  00000002  PC  76987698		WORD  [2] X'9876

Example  1  stores  the value of the 8/4 in a  word  starting  at 
00000000 PC.

Example 2 stores the value X'9876 (repeated twice).
.pa
5.3.4  SWORD pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>] SWORD [[<repetition-factor]] {<expression> |
                                                  <string>},,,

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          SWORD          is the pseudo-op.

          <repetition-factor>
                         (optional) specifies the number of times 
                         to  repeat the specified data word.   It 
                         must be an expression which evaluates to 
                         a    non-negative    immediate     type. 
                         <repetition-factor>  must be enclosed in 
                         square brackets "[]".

          <expression>   specifies the value of the data word. It 
                         must evaluate to an immediate type  with 
                         a value in the range -32768 to 32767.

          <string>       specifies a string constant.  Unless the 
                         string is a term in an expression it may 
                         be no longer than two characters.

The SWORD pseudo-op generates word length signed  constants.  The 
assembler  stores  the  words in the object file at  the  current 
address specified by the Location Counter. If <repetition-factor> 
is greater than one, or more than one  expression  is  specified, 
the  words are stored in consecutive ascending sequence  starting 
at the current address.  The least significant byte of a word  is 
stored at first and the most significant next.
NOTE:     <expression>  may have string constants  as  terms.  In 
          this  case the assembler treats the ASCII value of  the 
          string  as  a double-word integer.   The expression  is 
          evaluated and the result is stored in a single word.  A 
          string  used  in  a  term may  be  no  more  than  four 
          characters  in  length,  otherwise  an  error  will  be 
          reported.

Examples:

  1.  00000000  PC  FEFF		SWORD  -8/4
  2.  00000002  PC  76987698		SWORD  [2] X'9876

Example  1  stores the value of the -8/4 in a  word  starting  at 
00000000 PC.

Example 2 stores the value X'9876 (repeated twice).
.pa
5.3.5  DOUBLE pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>] DOUBLE [[<repetition-factor>]] {<expression> |
                                                    <string> },,,

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          DOUBLE         is the pseudo-op.

          <repetition-factor>
                         (optional) specifies the number of times 
                         to repeat the specified double-word.  It 
                         must be an expression which evaluates to 
                         a     non-negative    immediate    type. 
                         <repetition-factor> must be enclosed  in 
                         square brackets "[]".

          <expression>   specifies the value of the  double-word. 
                         It  must  evaluate to an immediate  type 
                         with a value in the range -2147483648 to 
                         2147483647.

          <string>       specifies  a string  constant.  No  more 
                         than  four  characters are allowed in  a 
                         string constant.

The DOUBLE pseudo-op generates double-word length constants.  The 
assembler  stores  the  double-words in the object  file  at  the 
current   address   specified  by  the   Location   Counter.   If 
<repetition-factor>  is  greater  than  one,  or  more  than  one  
expression    is  specified,   the  double-words  are  stored  in 
consecutive  ascending sequence starting at the current  address. 
The  least significant byte of a word is stored at first and  the 
most significant next.
NOTE:  <expression> may have string constants as terms.  In  this 
     case  the  assembler treats the ASCII value of the string as 
     a double-word integer.   The expression is evaluated and the 
     result  is stored in a word.  A string used in a term may be 
     no more than four characters in length,  otherwise an  error 
     will be reported.

Examples:

1. 00000000 PC 7654321001234567    DOUBLE  X'01234567, X'76543210
2. 00000008 PC 0505000050500000    DOUBLE  [2] 5

Example 1 stores the values X'01234567 and X'76543210 starting at 
00000000 PC.

Example 2 stores the value 5 (repeated twice).
5.3.6  SDOUBLE pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>] SDOUBLE [[<repetition-factor>]] {<expression> |
                                                     <string> },,,

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          SDOUBLE        is the pseudo-op.

          <repetition-factor>
                         (optional) specifies the number of times 
                         to repeat the specified double-word.  It 
                         must be an expression which evaluates to 
                         a     non-negative    immediate    type. 
                         <repetition-factor> must be enclosed  in 
                         square brackets "[]".

          <expression>   specifies  the value of the double-word. 
                         It  must evaluate to an  immediate  type 
                         with a value in the range -2147483648 to 
                         2147483647.

          <string>       specifies  a  string constant.  No  more 
                         than  four characters are allowed  in  a 
                         string constant.

The SDOUBLE pseudo-op generates double-word length constants. The 
Assembler  stores  the  double-words in the object  file  at  the 
current   address   specified  by  the   Location   Counter.   If 
<repetition-factor>  is  greater  than  one,  or  more  than  one  
expression    is  specified,   the  double-words  are  stored  in 
consecutive  ascending sequence starting at the current  address. 
The  least significant byte of a word is stored at first and  the 
most significant next.

NOTE: <expression>  may have string constants as terms.  In  this 
     case the assembler treats the ASCII value of the string as a 
     double-word  integer.   The expression is evaluated and  the 
     result is stored in a word.   A string used in a term may be 
     no  more than four characters in length,  otherwise an error 
     will be reported.

Examples:

  1.  00000000  PC  9CFFFFFF64000000	SDOUBLE  -100,100
  2.  00000008  PC  0505000050500000	SDOUBLE  [2] 5

Example 1 stores the values -100 and 100 starting at 00000000 PC.

Example 2 stores the value 5 (repeated twice).
5.3.7  FLOAT pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  FLOAT  [[<repetition-factor>]] {<expression>},,,

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          FLOAT          is the pseudo-op.

          <repetition-factor>
                         (optional) specifies the number of times 
                         to  repeat the specified floating  point 
                         number.  It  must be an expression which 
                         evaluates  to a  non-negative  immediate 
                         type.    <repetition-factor>   must   be 
                         enclosed in square brackets "[]".

          <expression>   specifies the value of a single floating 
                         point   number.     Strings   are    not 
                         permitted.  The  expression must specify 
                         the   number  only.   No   brackets   or 
                         operators are permissible.

The FLOAT pseudo-op generates only one single-precision floating-
point  constant per invocation.  The constants are stored at  the 
current  location counter.  Symbols assigned floating point  type 
are  stored internally in the assembler's symbol table as  double 
precision (32 bit) numbers until they are required. Conversion to 
single  precision  if necessary for a particular  instruction  is 
performed automatically by the assembler.

Examples:

  1  00000000 PC  DA0F4940		FLOAT  3.1415926
  2  00000004 PC  00007A4600007A46	FLOAT  [2] 16000.0

Example  1   stores  the floating-point constant  3.141526  in  a 
double-word starting at 00000000 PC.

Example  2  stores the floating-point constant 16000.0  (repeated 
twice).
.pa
5.3.8  LONG pseudo-op

Format: [<label>] LONG [[<repetition-factor>]] {<expression>},,,

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          LONG           is the pseudo-op.

          <repetition-factor>
                         (optional) specifies the number of times 
                         to  repeat the specified floating  point 
                         number.  It  must be an expression which 
                         evaluates  to  a non-negative  immediate 
                         type.    <repetition-factor>   must   be 
                         enclosed in square brackets "[]".

          <expression>   specifies the value of a single floating 
                         point number. Strings are not permitted. 
                         The  expression must specify the  number 
                         only.   No  brackets  or  operators  are 
                         permissible.

The  LONG pseudo-op generates only one double-precision floating-
point  constant per invocation.  The constants are stored at  the 
current  location counter.  Symbols assigned floating point  type 
are  stored internally in the Assembler's symbol table as  double 
precision (32 bit) numbers until they are required.

Examples:

  1.  00000000 PC  48D8124DFB210940	LONG	3.1415926
  2.  00000008 PC  000000000040CF40	LONG	[2] 16000.0
		   000000000040CF40

Example  1 stores the floating-point constant 3.141526 in  a  two 
double-words starting at 00000000 PC.

Example  2  stores the floating-point constant 16000.0  (repeated 
twice).
.pa
5.3.9  FIELD pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>] FIELD [<subfield-size>]<subfield-value>,,,

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          FIELD          is the pseudo-op.

          [<subfield-size>]
                         specifies  the length of the  bit  field 
                         being   generated.   It   may   be   any 
                         expression  which  evaluates to  a  non-
                         negative  immediate  type.   No  forward 
                         referenced   symbols   are    permitted.  
                         <subfield-size>   must  be  enclosed  in 
                         brackets  "[]".   The subfield  size  is 
                         required.

          <subfield-value>
                         specifies the field value. It may be any 
                         expression  which  evaluates to  a  non-
                         negative immediate type with a value  in 
                         the  range  specified by the field  size 
                         (e.g.,  0 to 15 for a 4-bit field,  0 to 
                         31  for  a 5-bit  field).  The  subfield 
                         value is required.

The FIELD pseudo-op generates one or more bit fields.  The fields 
are  stored  at  the current address specified  by  the  location 
counter.   Fields  are stored contiguously if there is more  than 
one   <subfield-size>  <subfield-value>  pair.  Zero  filling  of 

unused  bits  is performed by the assembler to the  nearest  byte 
boundary.

Multiple <subfield-size> <subfield-value> pairs must be separated 
by commas.

Examples:

  1.  00000000 PC 0B		FIELD  [5] 11
  2.  00000001 PC EB00		FIELD  [5] 11, [5] 7

Example  1 places 11 in a 5-bit field at address 00000000 PC  and 
zero fills the four high orders bits.

Example  2  places  11 and 7 in two consecutive 5-bit  fields  at 
address 00000001 PC and zero fills the 6 high order bits.
.pa
5.3.10  IF pseudo-op (Enhanced assembler only)

Format:   [<label>] IF <expression1> [<operator> <expression2>] 

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          IF             is the pseudo-op.

          <expression1>  the first expression which may  evaluate
                         to any type and a value. The value  must
                         not have any forward referenced symbols.

          <operator>     an   operator  that   separates  the two
                         expressions.

          <expression2>  the second expression which may evaluate
                         to any type and a value. The value  must
                         not have any forward referenced symbols.

The  IF pseudo-op enables the user to optional assemble  portions 
of  the  source.  If  only <expression1>  is  supplied  then  the 
assembler will evaluate the expression and if it is zero then the 
all  the code until an ENDIF pseudo-op is found will be  ignored. 
If  <expression1> <operator> <expression2> are all supplied  then 
the  assembler will evaluate <expression1> and <expression2>  and 
then  perform  the  magnitude test with the  <operator>.  If  the 
result is false then the assembler will ignore all the  following 
code until the corresponding ENDIF pseudo-op if found. IF - ENDIF 
pairs may be nested up to 15 deep.
Note. <operator> may be one of the following: <, >, <=, >=, or =.

Examples:

1. 00000000 PC         IF   4           ;This condition true
2. 00000000 PC 1400    MOVB R0,R0
3. 00000002            IF   23+5 > 23+5 ;This is false
4.                     MOVB R0,R0       ;Don't generate code
5.                     ENDIF            ;ENDIF for second IF
6. 00000002 PC 1400    MOVB R0,R0       ;Start generating code
7. 00000004 PC         ENDIF            ;Last ENDIF for first IF
.pa
5.3.11 ENDIF pseudo-op (Enhanced assembler only)

Format:   [<label>] ENDIF

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          ENDIF          is the pseudo-op.

The  ENDIF  pseudo-op  terminates an IF  invocation.  Each  ENDIF 
pseudo-op must be matched with one IF pseudo-op.  Thus,  they act 
as  a  pair  of markers that denote the beginning and  end  of  a 
portion  of  source code that is to be  conditionally  assembled. 

     The IF ENDIF pseudo ops ease the development of source  code 
that has various different modules that are to be included in the 
final product depending on various assembly time parameters.

     For examples of their use see Sec 5.3.10  above.  Note  that 
once  an IF is assembled that causes the code to follow it to not 
be  assembled it can only be terminated by its ENDIF pair.  IF  - 
ENDIF pairs may be nested up to 15 levels deep.
.pa
5.4  STORAGE ALLOCATION DIRECTIVES

There are five storage allocation pseudo-ops:

    Pseudo-op     Description
    ---------     -----------
      BLKB	  allocate byte storage
      BLKW	  allocate word storage
      BLKD	  allocate double-word storage
      BLKF	  allocate double-word(s) for floating-point
                  storage
      BLKL	  allocate quad-word(s) for long floating-point
                  storage

Storage allocation pseudo-ops have the following form:

     [<label>] <pseudo-op> [<expression>]

<expression>  specifies  the number of elements of the  specified 
length  to be allocated.   <expression> must evaluate to  a  non-
negative value of Immediate type. If symbols are used as terms in 
the expression they may not be forward referenced.  No storage is 
allocated  if the expression evaluates to zero.  If no expression 
is specified the assembler assigns a default value of 1.
Note. The storage allocation pseudo-ops generate zero initialised 
storage  in either PC relocation or SB relocation (only with  the 
enhanced version of the assembler). In all other relocation modes 
the space is reserved but not initialised.

The  form  of the storage allocation pseudo-ops is  described  in 
subsections 5.4.1 through 5.4.5.
.pa
5.4.1  BLKB pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  BLKB  [<expression>]

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          BLKB           is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   specifies  the  number  of bytes  to  be 
                         allocated.  It  must  be  an  expression 
                         which  evaluates to a non-negative value 
                         with Immediate type.

The  BLKB pseudo-op allocates <expression> bytes of  storage  for 
data.  The storage is allocated from the current location counter 
address.  The  storage  is  initialised to zero  if  the  current 
segment is PC relocation or SB relocation (only with the enhanced 
version of the assembler), otherwise the storage is allocated but 
not initialised.

Examples:

  1.  00000000 SB	 	BLKB   5
  2.  00000005 SB	HERE:	BLKB   11
  3.  00000010 SB		BLKB
  4.  00000011 SB		BLKB	($-HERE)/3

In  example 1,  five bytes of storage are allocated.  The storage 
starts at 00000000 SB.

In  example 2,  15 bytes of storage are  allocated.  The  storage 
starts at 00000005 SB.

In  example  3,  one  byte of storage is  allocated  starting  at 
address 00000010 SB.

In  example  4,  (17(SB)-5(SB))  bytes of storage  are  allocated 
starting at address 00000011 SB.
.pa
5.4.2  BLKW pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  BLKW  [<expression>]

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          BLKW           is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   specifies  the  number of  words  to  be 
                         allocated.   It  must  be an  expression 
                         which evaluates to a non-negative  value 
                         with Immediate type.

The  BLKW  pseudo-op allocates <expression> words of storage  for 
data.  The storage is allocated from the current location counter 
address.  The  storage  is  initialised to zero  if  the  current 
segment is PC relocation or SB relocation (only with the enhanced 
version of the assembler), otherwise the storage is allocated but 
not initialised.

Examples:

  1.  00000000 SB	 	BLKW   5
  2.  0000000A SB	HERE:	BLKW   11
  3.  00000020 SB		BLKW
  4.  00000022 SB		BLKW	($-HERE)/3

In example 1,  five words of storage are allocated.  The  storage 
starts at 00000000 SB.

In  example  2,  15 words of storage are allocated.  The  storage 
starts at 0000000A SB.

In  example  3,  one  word of storage is  allocated  starting  at 
address 00000020 SB.

In  example  4,  (22(SB)-10(SB)) words of storage  are  allocated 
starting at address 00000022 SB.
.pa
5.4.3  BLKD pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  BLKD  [<expression>]

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          BLKD           is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   specifies the number of double-words  to 
                         be allocated.   It must be an expression 
                         which  evaluates to a non-negative value 
                         with Immediate type.

The BLKD pseudo-op allocates <expression> double-words of storage 
for  data.  The  storage is allocated from the  current  location 
counter  address.  The  storage is initialised to  zeros  if  the 
current  segment is PC relocation or SB relocation (only with the 
enhanced  version  of the assembler),  otherwise the  storage  is 
allocated but not initialised.

Examples:

  1.  00000000 SB	 	BLKD   5
  2.  00000014 SB	HERE:	BLKD   11
  3.  00000040 SB		BLKD
  4.  00000044 SB		BLKD	($-HERE)/3

In  example 1,  five double-words of storage are  allocated.  The 
storage starts at 00000000 SB.

In  example  2,  15 double-words of storage  are  allocated.  The 
storage starts at 00000014 SB.

In example 3, one double-word of storage is allocated starting at 
address 00000040 SB.

In  example  4,   (44(SB)-14(SB))  double-words  of  storage  are 
allocated starting at address 00000044 SB.
.pa
5.4.4  BLKF pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  BLKF  [<expression>]

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          BLKF           is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   specifies  the number of double-words to 
                         be allocated.   It must be an expression 
                         which evaluates to a non-negative  value 
                         with Immediate type.

The BLKF pseudo-op allocates <expression> double-words of storage 
for  single  precision  floating  point  data.   The  storage  is 
allocated from the current location counter address.  The storage 
is  initialised to zeros if the current segment is PC  relocation 
or  SB  relocation  (only  with  the  enhanced  version  of   the 
assembler),   otherwise   the   storage  is  allocated  but   not 
initialised.

Examples:

  1.  00000000 SB	 	BLKF   5
  2.  00000014 SB	HERE:	BLKF   11
  3.  00000040 SB		BLKF
  4.  00000044 SB		BLKF	($-HERE)/3

In  example 1,  five double-words of storage are  allocated.  The 
storage starts at 00000000 SB.
In  example  2,  15 double-words of storage  are  allocated.  The 
storage starts at 00000014 SB.

In example 3, one double-word of storage is allocated starting at 
address 00000040 SB.

In  example  4,   (44(SB)-14(SB))  double-words  of  storage  are 
allocated starting at address 00000011 SB.
.pa
5.4.5  BLKL pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  BLKL  [<expression>]

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          BLKL           is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   specifies the number of quad-words to be 
                         allocated.   It  must  be an  expression 
                         which evaluates to a non-negative  value 
                         with Immediate type.

The  BLKL pseudo-op allocates <expression> quad-words of  storage 
for  double  precision  floating  point  data.   The  storage  is 
allocated from the current location counter address.  The storage 
is  initialised to zeros if the current segment is PC  relocation 
or  SB  relocation  (only  with  the  enhanced  version  of   the 
assembler),   otherwise   the   storage  is  allocated  but   not 
initialised.

Examples:

  1.  00000000 SB	 	BLKF   5
  2.  00000028 SB	HERE:	BLKF   11
  3.  00000080 SB		BLKF
  4.  00000088 SB		BLKF	($-HERE)/3

In  example  1,  five quad-words of storage  are  allocated.  The 
storage starts at 00000000 SB.
In example 2, 15 quad-words of storage are allocated. The storage 
starts at 00000028 SB.

In  example 3,  one quad-word of storage is allocated starting at 
address 00000080 SB.

In example 4, (88(SB)-28(SB)) quad-words of storage are allocated 
starting at address 00000088 SB.
.pa
5.5  LISTING CONTROL PSEUDO-OPS

The  listing control pseudo-ops do not affect code generation  in 
any way.   They are purely for controlling the format of the list 
file produced by the DSI-32 Assembler.

    Pseudo-op       Description
    ---------       -----------
    TITLE	    defines the title to place at the top of each 
                    listing page
    SUBTITLE	    defines  the subtitle to be placed  one  line 
                    below the title
    NOLIST	    all  lines until the next LIST pseudo-op  are 
                    not listed
    LIST            restarts the listing of all lines
    EJECT           force a form feed in the list file
    WIDTH	    performs no function (only for compatibility)

The listing control pseudo-ops are described in subsections 5.5.1 
through 5.5.6.
.pa
5.5.1  TITLE pseudo-ops

Format:   [<label>]  TITLE <string>

description:
          <label>        is an option label.

          TITLE          is the pseudo-op.

          <string>       may be up to eighty characters long. The 
                         string must be enclosed in quotes (which 
                         are  not  printed).   The  format  of  a 
                         string  is  the  same  as  described  in 
                         subsection 2.4.3. The title is displayed 
                         at the top of each listing page.

The  TITLE  pseudo-op  allows  the user  supplied  string  to  be 
displayed at the top of each page of the program listing.

If  the more than one TITLE pseudo-op occurs in a program the new 
string will be displayed at the top of each subsequent page.

No title is printed if no TITLE pseudo-op is specified.

Example:

	TITLE  "Floating point subroutines"

The example causes the string "Floating point subroutines" to  be 
displayed at the top of the current page of the program listing.
.pa
5.5.2  SUBTITLE pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  SUBTITLE <string>

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          SUBTITLE       is the pseudo-op.

          <string>       may   be  up  to  eighty  characters  in 
                         length.  The string must be enclosed  in 
                         quotes  (which  are not  printed).   The 
                         format  of  the string is  the  same  as 
                         described   in  subsection  2.4.3.   The 
                         subtitle is displayed at the top of each 
                         page after the title (if there is one).

The SUBTITLE pseudo-op enables the user to specify a string to be 
displayed  at the top of each page of the  program  listing.  The 
subtitle will be displayed below the title, if specified.
The  SUBTITLE pseudo-op will cause the string to be displayed  at 
the  top of the current page if it is the first statement on  the 
line, otherwise only subsequent page are affected.
If  more  than  one SUBTITLE pseudo-op occurs in a  program  each 
occurrence will affect only the subsequent pages.
No subtitle is displayed if no SUBTITLE pseudo-op is specified.
Example:

	SUBTITLE  "Subroutine divide"

The  example causes the string "Subroutine divide" to be  printed 
at  the top of the current page if it is the first  statement  on 
the page, otherwise it is printed at the top of the next page.
.pa
5.5.3  NOLIST pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  NOLIST

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          NOLIST         is the pseudo-op.

The  NOLIST  pseudo-op causes the assembler to stop  listing  all 
subsequent  lines.  The lines are assembled,  but not directed to 
the listing file.  Error messages will still be displayed.

Example:

	NOLIST
	ADDB	0(SB),R5
	MULW	R3,MATHS
	JSR	SPECIAL
	LIST

In  the  example the NOLIST pseudo-op suppresses the printing  of 
three  lines of text.  Listing of text is restarted by  the  LIST 
pseudo-op.
.pa
5.5.4  LIST pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  LIST

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          LIST           is the pseudo-op.

The  LIST  pseudo-op  restarts the listing  of  assembler  source 
lines.   The listings of source lines is suppressed by the NOLIST 
pseudo-op.

Example:

	NOLIST
	ADDB	0(SB),R5
	MULW	R3,MATHS
	JSR	SPECIAL
	LIST
NXT:	BEQ	DONE

In the example the LIST pseudo-op restarts the listing after  the 
which was stopped by the NOLIST pseudo-op.
.pa
5.5.5  EJECT pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  EJECT

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          EJECT          is the pseudo-op.

The  EJECT pseudo-op causes the assembler to force a form feed to 
a  new page.   The statement containing the EJECT pseudo-op  does 
not appear on the listing.
.pa
5.5.6  WIDTH pseudo-op

Format:   [<label>]  WIDTH  <expression>

description:
          <label>        is an optional label.

          WIDTH          is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   must evaluate to an immediate type.

Note.  This  pseudo-op performs no function and is  included  for 
compatibility with other 32000 assemblers.
.pa
5.6  LINKAGE CONTROL PSEUDO-OPS

The  linkage control pseudo-ops enable the programmer to  specify 
which  symbols  are global and which symbols are external to  the 
module being assembled.

   Pseudo-op	Description
   ---------	-----------
   IMPORT	specifies external symbols
   IMPORTP	specifies external procedure symbols
   EXPORT	specifies public symbols
   EXPORTP	specifies public procedure symbols
   COMM         specifies public symbol of given length

A  public symbol is a symbol that has been defined by  an  EXPORT 
pseudo-op,  or an EXPORTP pseudo-op or double colon (::). It must 
have PC, ABS or SB relocation type.

An  external  symbol  is a symbol that has been defined  with  an 
IMPORT pseudo-op,  IMPORTP pseudo-op or colon minus (:-).  It  is 
assigned  EXT relocation type,  and refers to a symbol in another 
module.  Every  external  symbol must correspond to  exactly  one 
public symbol.

A public symbol with a specific name may be exported by only  one 
module.   The  same symbol may be imported by many  modules.  The 
linker  satisfies  the public and external symbol  references  at 
link time.  An error occurs if an imported symbol has no matching 
exported symbol.

A symbol may be both exported and imported by the same module. To 
all  other  modules the symbol behaves as though it was  exported 
only.  To the module in which it was exported, though, the linker 
builds  a link table entry for the symbol in the  current  module 
table.  This  allows  the  symbol to be recursively  called  from 
the module in which it is defined.

Subsections  5.6.1  through 5.6.4 describe  the  linkage  control 
pseudo-ops.
.pa
5.6.1  IMPORT pseudo-op

Format:   IMPORT <symbol>,,,

description:
          IMPORT         is the pseudo-op.

          <symbol>       is  the  name of a  public  symbol.  The 
                         symbol must be defined in another module 
                         and  it  must  have  PC,   SB,   or  ABS 
                         relocation  type.  More than one  symbol 
                         may be specified per line,  each  symbol 
                         must be separated by a comma.

The  IMPORT  pseudo-op defines external symbols  which  reference 
data in some other module.  The IMPORT pseudo-op must not be used 
to  import  external  procedures,   the  IMPORTP  pseudo-op  (see 
subsection 5.6.2) should be used.

The  symbol  is  entered  into the assembler's  symbol  table  at 
assembly time.   It is assigned EXT type, an offset of zero and a 
Link  Table number which starts at zero and increments  for  each 
imported  symbol whether it is imported by the IMPORT or  IMPORTP 
pseudo-ops.
NOTE:     The  line on which the symbol is imported  must  appear 
          before  any  other statement which references the  same 
          symbol.  Otherwise,  an  error will be reported by  the 
          assembler.

          Since  the external symbol references are only resolved 
          at link time,  only then will an error be reported  for 
          mismatched symbols.

Example:

	IMPORT	ONE, TWO, THREE

In  the example if the symbols are the first imported symbols  in 
the program then,  ONE is assigned link table entry zero,  TWO is 
assigned one and THREE is assigned two.
.pa
5.6.2  IMPORTP pseudo-op

Format:   IMPORTP <symbol>,,,

description:
          IMPORTP        is the pseudo-op.

          <symbol>       is  the  name of a  public  symbol.  The 
                         symbol must be defined in another module 
                         and  it  must  have  PC,   SB,   or  ABS 
                         relocation  type.  More than one  symbol 
                         may be specified per line,  each  symbol 
                         must be separated by a comma.

The  IMPORTP  pseudo-op defines external symbols which  reference 
external procedures in some other module.  The IMPORTP  pseudo-op 
must  not  be  used to import data,  the  IMPORT  pseudo-op  (see 
subsection 5.6.1) should be used.

The  symbol  is  entered into the  assembler's  symbol  table  at 
assembly time.   It is assigned EXT type, an offset of zero and a 
Link  Table  number which starts at zero and increments for  each 
imported  symbol whether it is imported by the IMPORT or  IMPORTP 
pseudo-ops.

NOTE:     The  line  on which the symbol is imported must  appear 
          before  any other statement which references  the  same 
          symbol.   Otherwise  an  error will be reported by  the 
          assembler.

          Since the external symbol references are only  resolved 
          at  link  time,only then will an error be reported  for 
          mismatched symbols.

Example:

	IMPORT	ONE, TWO, THREE

In  the example if the symbols are the first imported symbols  in 
the program then,  ONE is assigned link table entry zero,  TWO is 
assigned one and THREE is assigned two.
.pa
5.6.3  EXPORT pseudo-op

Format:   EXPORT <symbol>,,,

description:
          EXPORT         is the pseudo-op.

          <symbol>       is the name of a symbol which is defined 
                         in the current module.  It must have one 
                         of the following relocation  types:  PC, 
                         ABS,  or SB. More than one symbol may be 
                         exported  per line,  each symbol must be 
                         separated by a comma.

The  EXPORT pseudo-op enables a symbol to be given public  scope. 
The symbol may then be imported by an IMPORT pseudo-op in another 
module.  A  symbol which has been exported from a module  may  be 
used   in  that  module  as  an  instruction  operand  or  in  an 
expression.  The  EXPORT  pseudo-op must not be  used  to  export 
procedures.  The  EXPORTP pseudo-op (see subsection 5.6.4) should 
be used.

A  symbol  may  be exported by following its  definition  with  a 
double-colon (::).   If the double colon (::) is used without the 
PROC  pseudo-op (Section 6.2),  then the symbol is assumed to  be 
referencing data.

NOTE:     A symbol which appears after the EXPORT statement  must 
          also  be defined in some statement following the EXPORT 
          statement.  Otherwise an error will be reported by  the 
          assembler.
Example:

	EXPORT	ONE, TWO, THREE

In the example three symbols are assigned public scope:  ONE, TWO 
and THREE.
.pa
5.6.4  EXPORTP pseudo-op

Format:   EXPORTP <symbol>,,,

description:
          EXPORT         is the pseudo-op.

          <symbol>       is the name of a symbol which is defined 
                         in the current module.  It must have one 
                         of  the following relocation types:  PC, 
                         ABS,  or SB. More than one symbol may be 
                         exported per line,  each symbol must  be 
                         separated by a comma.

The EXPORTP pseudo-op enables a symbol to be given public  scope. 
The  symbol  may  then  be imported by an  IMPORTP  pseudo-op  in 
another  module.  A symbol which has been exported from a  module 
may  be  used in that module as an instruction operand or  in  an 
expression.  The  EXPORTP  pseudo-op must not be used  to  export 
data. The EXPORT pseudo-op (see subsection 5.6.3) should be used.

A  symbol  may  be exported by following its  definition  with  a 
double-colon  (::).   If the double colon (::) is used  with  the 
PROC  pseudo-op (Section 6.2),  then the symbol is assumed to  be 
referencing an external procedure.

NOTE:     A symbol which appears after the EXPORTP statement must 
          also be defined in some statement following the EXPORTP 
          statement.  Otherwise  an error will be reported by the 
          assembler.

Example:

	EXPORTP	ONE, TWO, THREE

In the example three symbols are assigned public scope:  ONE, TWO 
and THREE.
.pa
5.6.5 COMM pseudo-op (Enhanced assembler only)

Format:   COMM   <symbol>,length

description:
          COMM           is the pseudo-op.

          <symbol>       is the  name of a symbol which is to  be 
                         imported  from  some other  module.  The 
                         symbol refers to a data item.

          length         is the length of the data item.  If  the 
                         symbol  is  not  defined  in  any  other 
                         module  via  an export then  the  linker 
                         will  assign  the variable and  allocate 
                         enough  static base data to satisfy  the 
                         length specifier.  The data item is also 
                         zeroed by the linker.

The  COMM  pseudo-op  enables a data item  to  be  accessed  from 
another  module or to be created by the linker at link time.  The 
COMM  pseudo op enables the assembler to support the  concept  of 
named common such as required by languages such as Fortran.
Example:

	COMM   FRED,10

In  the  example the data item FRED is imported from some  module 
and  its length is 10 bytes.  If FRED is satisfied by some  other 
module  at  link time then the length specifier will  be  ignored 
else  the linker will create a dummy module and allocate 10 bytes 
for  the data item.  The linker will also create an entry in  the 
appropriate Link Table.
.pa
5.7  SEGMENT CONTROL PSEUDO-OPS

The  segment control pseudo-ops enable the programmer to  control 
the  Assembler's  current relocation mode and the  value  of  the 
location counter. The segment control pseudo-ops are described in 
detail below:

     pseudo-op	   Description
     ---------	   -----------
     DSECT	   location counter set to IM relocation mode
     PROGRAM	   location counter set to PC relocation mode
     STATIC	   location counter set to SB relocation mode
     LOC	   location counter set to the specified value
     ENDSEG	   location counter and relocation mode set to
		   the values prior to the current segment
     ALIGN	   location counter set to the specified offset

The  segment  control pseudo-ops enable the programmer to  define 
various  program  segments.  Each segment contains data  or  code 
relative to the segment base.  The various data or code  segments 
are assigned contiguous addresses by the assembler, the FP and SP 
segments  are  the only exception to this rule.  Since  they  are 
actually  relative to the stack they only exist for the  duration 
of a procedure invocation etc.

The  form  and description of the segment control  pseudo-ops  is 
described in subsections 5.7.1 through 5.7.6.
.pa
5.7.1  DSECT pseudo-op

Format:   DSECT

description:
          DSECT          is the pseudo-op.

The DSECT pseudo-op defines a dummy segment. This enables symbols 
to  be  assigned  immediate type and a  particular  value.  These 
symbols  may  then be used within expressions or as  operands  in 
instructions.  These  symbols may only be referenced  after  they 
have been defined in a segment.

The  location  counter  is  set  to an offset of  0  and  the  IM 
relocation  mode.   No object code is produced for  this  segment 
type.

Example:

	DSECT
ONE:	BLKB	1
TWO:	BLKB	2
THREE:	BLKB	3
	ENDSEG

In  the  example three symbols are assigned Immediate  type.  The 
symbols  ONE,  TWO  and  THREE are assigned values  0,  1  and  3 
respectively.

The symbols may then be used to reference data.  Since their type 
is  Immediate they may be used as displacements in  frame  memory 
operands. The following example shows one use of these symbols:

	ADDB	1,ONE(FP)
	SUBB	2,TWO(FP)
	MULD	3,THREE(FP)
.pa
5.7.2  PROGRAM pseudo-ops

Format:	PROGRAM

description:

	PROGRAM		is the pseudo-op.

The  PROGRAM  pseudo-op  defines a  program  code  segment.   The 
instructions and constant data is stored in this segment.

The  location counter is set to PC relocation mode the offset  to 
the  next  available PC address (initially  zero).  The  location 
counter is incremented after every instruction.

The program code segment is the only segment in which object code 
is generated. All other segments only reserve storage relative to 
one of the segment bases.

Example:

	PROGRAM

In the example the Location Counter is set to PC relocation mode. 
The offset is set to the next PC address.
.pa
5.7.3  STATIC pseudo-op

Format:   STATIC

description:
          STATIC         is the pseudo-op.

The  STATIC pseudo-op defines a static base segment.  The  static 
base segment is relative to the SB register,  which is automatic-
ally loaded when a module is first entered. Forward references to 
symbols defined in static base segments are allowed.

The  symbols in a static base segment are assigned  monotonically 
increasing addresses which start at 0 for the first symbol in the 
first static base segment.   The location counter for the  static 
base  relocation mode may not be decremented thus it is saved  on 
entering a different relocation mode.

The  static  base segment contains storage allocation  pseudo-ops 
only.   No  instructions or pseudo-ops which generate code  (e.g. 
DOUBLE, FIELD, etc) may be used.

Example:

	STATIC
ONE:	BLKB	1
TWO:	BLKB	2
THREE:	BLKB	3
	ENDSEG

In  the  example  three  symbols are defined  in  a  static  base 
segment.  The  STATIC  pseudo-op sets the location counter to  SB 
relocation mode and to the next available SB address.
.pa
5.7.4  LOC pseudo-op

Format:   LOC [<expression>]

description:
          LOC		is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   defines   a  new  relocation  mode   and 
                         offset.  The expression must evaluate to 
                         a  value with IM,  PC,  SB,  FP,  or  SP 
                         relocation mode.

The  LOC  pseudo-op  causes a new  segment  to  be  entered.  The 
location   counter   is  set  to  the  value  specified  by   the 
expression.

If  the  expression evaluates to SP or FP  relocation  mode,  any 
value is allowed.  If the relocation mode is IM,  PC,  or SB, the 
expression's value must evaluate to a value greater than or equal 
to  the  last value for the particular relocation  mode.  If  the 
Relocation  Mode  is PC,  the  assembler will output  zero  value 
bytes  till the location counter reaches the address specified by 
<expression>.

The location counter is incremented after each instruction in IM, 
PC and SB relocation modes.  The location counter is  decremented 
in the FP and SP relocation modes.
Examples:

  1.	LOC  12
  2.	LOC  12(FP)
  3.	LOC  12(PC)

Example  1 assigns IM relocation mode and an offset of 12 to  the 
location counter.

Example  2 assigns FP relocation mode and an offset of 12 to  the 
location counter.

Example  3 assigns PC relocation mode and an offset of 12 to  the 
location counter.
.pa
5.7.5  ENDSEG pseudo-op

Format:   ENDSEG

description:
          ENDSEG         is the pseudo-op.

The  ENDSEG  pseudo-op  cause  the current  segment  to  end  and 
restores  the  location counter relocation mode and value it  had 
before  the  current segment was entered by one  of  the  segment 
pseudo-ops (see subsections 5.7.1 through 5.7.4).

Each  DSECT,  PROGRAM,  STATIC  and  LOC pseudo-op  must  have  a 
matching ENDSEG pseudo-op.

NOTE:     The  assembler  assigns  a default value  and  type  of 
          00000000  PC to the location counter at the start of an 
          assembly  thus  a  program	may  have  no  opening 
          pseudo-op and no ENDSEG and still be valid.

Example:

00000000 PC			     1  	PROGRAM
00000000 PC CEE0D6C0000000C00000     2  	MULB  TEST1,TEST2
00000000 SB			     3  	STATIC
00000000 SB			     4  TEST1:	BLKB	4
00000004 SB 			     5  	ENDSEG
0000000B PC 0C00		     6  TEST2:	WORD	12
0000000D PC CEFCD6007E		     7  	DIVB  TEST1,TEST2
00000012 PC 			     8  	ENDSEG
00000000 FP 			     9  	LOC	0(FP)
FFFFFFF6 FP			    10  TEST3:	BLKB	10
FFFFFFF6 FP 			    11  	ENDSEG

In  the  example  the  ENDSEG  pseudo-op  terminates  the   three 
segments: PC, SB and the FP segments.
.pa
5.7.6  ALIGN pseudo-op

Format:   ALIGN <expression1> [,<expression2>]

description:
          ALIGN          is the pseudo-op.

          <expression1>	 defines  the  base  of  a  new  location 
                         counter   value.   The  expression  must 
                         evaluate  to  a  non-negative  value  of 
                         Immediate  type.   No forward references 
                         to symbols are permitted.

          <expression2>	 optional  expression which  defines  the 
                         offset   of  the  new  location  counter 
                         value. The expression must evaluate to a 
                         non-negative value of Immediate type and 
                         must  be  less  than  <expression1>   in 
                         value. If <expression2> is not specified 
                         it takes on a default value of zero (0). 
                         No  forward  references to  symbols  are 
                         permitted.

The  ALIGN  pseudo-op  enables the location counter value  to  be 
changed while still maintaining the current relocation mode.  The 
new  value  is the sum of a multiple of  <expression1>,  and  the 
<expression2> and is always equal to or greater than the  current 
location counter.  The value satisfies the following definition:

	new value MODULUS  <expression1> = <expression2>

If  only <expression1> is specified,  the new value is a multiple 
of <expression1> only. The new value is the multiple of the basis 
that  is  greater than or equal to the current location  counter. 
For  example,  if  <expression1> is 8 and  the  current  location 
counter is 25, then the new value is 32 (i.e. 4*8).

If  both <expression1> and <expression2> are specified,  the  new 
value is the sum of the multiple of the basis and the offset. For 
example,  if  <expression1>  is 8,  <expression2> is 5,  and  the 
current  location counter is 25,  then the new value is 29  (i.e. 
3*8+5).

NOTE:     The ALIGN pseudo-op may only be used when assembly mode 
          is  standard.   If the ALIGN pseudo-op is used in a  PC 
          relocation  segment,  the Assembler will zero-fill  all 
          bytes  between  the  current  PC address  and  the  new 
          address     calculated    from    <expression1>     and 
          <expression2>.
.pa
Example:

00000000 SB			   1		STATIC
00000000 SB                        2  TEST1:	BLKW	1
00000002 SB			   3		ALIGN   5
00000005 SB			   4  TEST2:	BLKW
00000007 SB			   5		ALIGN   12, 3
0000000F SB			   6  TEST3:	BLKW
00000011 SB			   7		ENDSEG

In  the  example two ALIGN pseudo-ops  appear.  In  line  3,  the 
pseudo-op sets the location counter to a multiple of 5. Since the 
location counter is 00000002  SB,  the new value will be 00000005 
SB i.e., 1*5. In line 5, the pseudo-ops sets the location counter 
to a multiple of 12 plus 5. Since the current location counter is 
7, the the new value will be 15 i.e., 1*12+3.
.pa
5.8  MODULE CONTROL PSEUDO-OPS

There   are  two  module  control  pseudo-ops  which  enable  the 
programmer  to  specify  the module name  and  the  module  start 
address:

     pseudo-op		Description
     ---------		-----------
     MODULE		defines the module's name
     START		defines the module's execution address

Subsections  5.8.1 and 5.8.2 describe the module control  pseudo-
ops.

5.8.1  MODULE pseudo-op

Format:   MODULE <symbol>

description:
          MODULE         is the pseudo-op.

          <symbol>       defines the name of the current module.

The MODULE pseudo-op defines the name of the current module. Only 
one  MODULE pseudo-op is allowed per assembler source  file.  The 
pseudo-op may appear anywhere in the file. The name of the source 
file  is  used  as  the module name if  no  MODULE  pseudo-op  is 
specified.
Example:

	MODULE	MSUBRT

In the example the symbol MSUBRT is assigned as the module name.
.pa
5.8.2  START pseudo-op

Format:   START [<expression>]

description:
          START          is the pseudo-op.

          <expression>   specifies the module's execution address.

The  START pseudo-op specifies where execution is to  start.  The 
expression must evaluate to a value with PC relocation type.   If 
a  START pseudo-op is not specified,  the assembler defaults  the 
start address to 00000000 PC.

The START pseudo-op assigns the module as the MAIN module.

